254. quin ...reice ...amone recipis. Plautus uses quin in ex- hortation both with imper. and indic. Ussing objects to both moods being used together and alters to recipe tc tuom: Lambinus changed all three verbs into the indic. But Miiller(Nachtr‘zige p. 5) defends the passage as it stands, and the most recent editors (Leo, Goetz and Schoell) print it with- out alteration.

Donatus distinguishes socordiam of mental sluggishness from segni- tiem of sluggishness in action. ⁸ Segnz'liem αιί agendum, socordiam ad considerandzmz.’ chnz'tiem (not segm'liam): so mollities, ma- series, tristities, pauperies, nequi- lies in noni. and acc. only. See Brix on Mil. 1203.

255. ad ingenium uetus uor- sutum te recipis tuom, ‘go back to your old crastiness.’ cf. Ter. Adelph. 71 si sperat clam fore, rursum ad ingenium redit.

256. caue faxis, ‘mind you don’t do.' Cane with simple sub- junctive is common in 2nd person, especially in poetry. Cf. caue dicas, caue siris, ἃς. Faxc'm, mrim, capsim, ἃς. are properly opta- tives of an original sigmatic aorist.

quo hanc celocem conferam? ‘whither am I to steer this de· spatch-boat?‘ i.e. myself. Cf. Mil. 986, Epid. 74, Pseud. 1306.

259. inpetritum. lupario is the augural form of inpetro. See Cic. de Diuin. 1. 16. 28, 11. 15· 35. Libanus says he has taken the auspices and the omens are all ν good. The birds let him take what direction he pleases (quouis admittunt).

260. picus et cornix ab laeua, coruos, parra ab dextera.. See Epid. 184* (note). Some birds were favourable if seen on the right, others if seen on the lest. Cic. de Diuin. 1. 39. 85 cur a dextra coruus, a sinistra cornix faciat ratum? agrees with the pre- sent passage. On the other hand Aul. 624 non temere est, quod coruos cantat milti nunc ab laena manu is a bad omen. But here they are all favourable. The birds seen on the left are those which when seen on the left are of good omen, and so with those that are seen on the right. On ab used of the side con— cernecl see Roby 1813.
